  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">We extended our formulation of causal dissipative hydrodynamics [T. Koide et al., Phys. Rev. \textbf{C75}, 034909 (2007)] to be applicable to the ultra-relativistic regime by taking the finite size of the fluid cells into account. The new equation has a non-linear term which suppresses the effect of viscosity. We found that such a term is necessary to guarantee the positive definiteness of the inertia term and stabilize numerical calculations in ultra-relativistic initial conditions. Because of the suppression of the viscosity, the behavior of the fluid is more close to that of the ideal fluid. Our result is essentially same as that from the extended irreversible thermodynamics, but is different from the Israel-Stewart theory. A possible origin of the difference is discussed.</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">arXiv</subfield>
  </datafield>
